'''Tool''' is an [[United States|American]] [[Rock music|rock]] [[Band (music)|band]], formed during 1990 in [[Los Angeles, California|Los Angeles]], [[California]], that consists of drummer [[Danny Carey]], bassist [[Justin Chancellor]], guitarist [[Adam Jones]], and vocalist [[Maynard James Keenan]].

Emerging with a "slam and bang" [[Heavy metal music|heavy metal]] sound on their first release,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://toolshed.down.net/faq/faq.html | title=E8 | work=The Tool FAQ | accessdate=2006-03-07 | author=Kabir Akhtar }}</ref> when heavy metal was dominated by [[thrash metal]], they were later seen at the top of the [[alternative metal]] movement with the release of their second full-length studio album ''[[<U+00C6>nima]]'' in 1996.<ref name="rollingstoneaenima">{{cite web | url=http://www.rollingstone.com/artists/tool/albums/album/223371/review/5940520/aenima | year=1996| title=<U+00C6>nima Review | work=Rolling Stone | accessdate=2007-04-08 | author=David Fricke }}</ref> After an ongoing evolution of their sound and continuous efforts to unify musical experimentation, visual arts, and a message of personal evolution<ref name="livewire">{{cite web | url=http://toolshed.down.net/articles/index.php?action=view-article&id=February_1997--Livewire.html | title=Angry Jung Men! (transcript) | year=1997 | work=Livewire Magazine | accessdate=2007-04-08 | author=Loraine Gennaro}}</ref> on ''[[Lateralus]]'' (2001), their most recent album ''[[10,000 Days]]'' (2006), as well as respective tours, they are generally described as a style-transgressing act and part of [[Progressive rock|progressive]]<ref name="rollingstonelateralus">{{cite web | url=http://www.rollingstone.com/reviews/album/_/id/211444?rnd=1145911827234 | year=2001| title=Lateralus Review | work=Rolling Stone | accessdate=2006-04-24 | author=David Fricke | quote = Drums, bass and guitars move in jarring cycles of hyperhowl and near-silent death march. [...] In another era, Lateralus - co-produced by Tool and engineer David Bottrill - would have been considered progressive rock, [...]}}</ref> and [[art rock]].<ref name="AllMusic_Biography"/>

Their aspirational work features exceptionally long or complex releases,<ref name="AMG Lateralus review">{{cite web | url=http://www.allmusic.com/cg/amg.dll?p=amg&sql=10:bv851vg3zz9a | year=2001| title=Lateralus Review | work=AllMusic | accessdate=2006-04-28 | author=Rob Theakston}}</ref> controversial yet abstract lyrics,<ref name="livewire"/> and unorthodox music videos, which results in a rather ambivalent relationship between the band and today's [[music industry]],<ref name="Stepping Out From the Shadows">{{cite web | date=May 23, 2001 | url=http://www.exclaim.ca/index.asp?layid=22&csid=1&csid1=685 | work=Exclaim! | title=Tool - Stepping Out From the Shadows | accessdate=2006-09-17 | author=Roman Sokal }}</ref> at times marked by [[Censorship of music|censorship]],<ref name="stinkfist">{{cite web | url=http://toolshed.down.net/video/stinkfist/track1.html | title=The "Track #1" Fiasco | accessdate=2006-03-06 | author=Kabir Akhtar | format=TXT}}</ref> and the band's ongoing struggle for privacy.<ref name="livewire"/>

Nevertheless, Tool receives critical acclaim, has won [[Grammy Award]]s, performs worldwide tours, and produces albums that top the charts in several countries.<ref name="AllMusic Biography"/> Between album releases, the band takes extended breaks that allow for collaboration with other artists to design award-winning album packaging, elaborate light shows and form notable side-projects.<ref name="classicrock2001">{{cite web | url=http://toolshed.down.net/articles/index.php?action=view-article&id=August_2001--Classic_Rock.html | title=Home Improvement | year=2001 | month=August | accessdate=2007-05-12 | work=Classic Rock | author=Rosanna Slater | format=TXT | quote=During Tool's recent hiatus, he (Carey) drummed with Pigface [...], and the Dead Kennedy's Jello Biafra, Revolting Cocks, and Ministry's Paul Barker [...], while Jones joined Melvins singer King Buzzo in experimentalists Noise Arcade. Keenan, in particular, took advantage of time away from Tool, providing vocals for the Deftones' 'White Pony' album, debuting with Tori Amos [...], and working with Nine Inch Nails' Trent Reznor [...]. Most notably, he also formed A Perfect Circle [...].}}</ref>

== History ==
=== Early years (1990<U+2013>1992) ===
During the 1980s, the future members of Tool had all moved to Los Angeles. Both [[Paul d'Amour]] and [[Adam Jones]] wanted to enter the film industry, while [[Maynard James Keenan]] studied arts and later worked applying spatial design concepts to remodeling pet stores.<ref name="livewire"/> [[Danny Carey]] performed as a drummer for [[Green Jell<U+00FF>]],<ref>{{cite web | title= Cereal Killer | publisher=imdb.com | url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0355502/ | accessdate=2007-05-09}}</ref> was a studio drummer for [[Carole King]], and played around Los Angeles with [[Pigmy Love Circus]].<ref>{{cite web | title =Tool Bio: Danny Carey | publisher =Toolband.com | url =http://www.toolband.com/identity/danny/main.html | accessdate =2007-05-08 }}</ref>

Keenan and Jones met through a mutual friend and started [[jam session|jamming]] together around the end of the decade. Carey happened to live above Keenan and was introduced to Jones by [[Tom Morello]], an old high school friend of Jones and former bandmate of [[Electric Sheep (band)|Electric Sheep]].<ref>{{cite book
| title = The New Metal Masters | author = HP Newquist, Rich Maloof | publisher = Backbeat Books
| date = [[2004-04-21]] | isbn = 978-0879308049 | pages = 12 | accessdate = 2007-04-08
}}</ref> Carey played in their sessions because he "felt kinda sorry for them," as other invited musicians were not showing up.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://toolshed.down.net/faq/faq.html|title=C3|work=The Tool FAQ|author=Kabir Akhtar|format=TXT}}</ref> A friend of Jones later introduced them to bassist d'Amour, who completed the band.<ref name="circusmagazine">{{cite web | date=May 31, 1994 | url=http://toolshed.down.net/articles/index.php?action=view-article&id=May_1994--Circus_Magazine.html | work=Circus Magazine | title=A Sober Look At Tool | accessdate=2007-04-09 | author=Katherine Turman }}</ref> Only three months later, Tool would sign a record deal with [[Zoo Entertainment]].<ref name="circusmagazine"/>

Zoo published the band's first effort ''[[Opiate (album)|Opiate]]'' in March 1992, borrowing its name from [[Karl Marx]]'s famous quote, "[[Opium of the People|Religion is the opium of the People]]."<ref name="diCarlointerview">{{cite web | author = Christopher W. diCarlo | title = Interview with Maynard James Keenan | url=http://www.cdicarlo.com/paper_04maynard.htm | accessdate = 2007-05-04 }}</ref> The six-song [[Extended play|EP]] included the "hardest sounding" songs the band had written to that point, among them the singles "[[Hush (Tool song)|Hush]]" and "Opiate".<ref name="Jones a Master of Many Trades">{{cite web | url=http://toolshed.down.net/articles/text/gsch.mar.94.html | title=Tool Guitarist Adam Jones is a Master of Many Trades | work=Guitar School | year=1994|accessdate=2006-04-07}}</ref> A music video for "Hush" was created to promote the single, and the band's dissenting views about the then-prominent [[Parents Music Resource Center|PMRC]] and its advocacy of [[censorship of music]]. The band members appeared naked, only their genitalia covered with the PMRC-promoted [[Parental Advisory|parental advisory]] stickers<ref name="much">{{cite web
| url = http://toolshed.down.net/articles/index.php?action=view-article&id=February_1997--Muchmusic.html
| title = Tool Muchmusic spotlight: transcribed interview
| author = Theresa Roncon
| publisher = [[MuchMusic]], transcribed by Rory Mitchell for The Tool Page
| year = 1997
| month = February
| accessdate = 2007-04-09
}}</ref> and their mouths covered by duct tape in symbolic protest. To support ''Opiate'' the band began touring with [[Rollins Band]], Skitzo, [[Fishbone]], and [[Rage Against the Machine]]<ref name="Stepping Out From the Shadows"/> to positive responses, giving the band a strong start into their musical career.<ref name="much">{{cite web
| url = http://toolshed.down.net/articles/index.php?action=view-article&id=September_1992--RIP_Magazine.html
| title = Fresh Blood (transcription)
| work = RIP magazine
| author = Janiss Garza
| publisher = RIP Magazine (transcription by t.d.n.)
| year = 1992
| month = September
| accessdate = 2007-06-04
quote= Tool's debut for Zoo records is Opiate, a six song EP. It stands out like a glowing red lump of coal in a bin of man-made diamonds-raw, real and honest. [...] Although Maynard is glad the buzz on the band has gotten off to a strong start, [...]
}}</ref>

=== ''Undertow'' (1993<U+2013>1995) ===

[[Image:Screenshot tool sober lollapalooza 93 mtv clip.jpg|thumb|right|Tool's [[Lollapalooza]] 1993 performance was an important step in boosting their popularity. Above the band performs "[[Sober (song)|Sober]]". Left to right: Jones, Keenan, Carey.]]
The following year, Tool was able to release their first full-length album, ''[[Undertow (Tool album)|Undertow]]'' (1993), because many of the songs on ''Undertow'' had already been written at the time ''Opiate'' was released.<ref name="Jones a Master of Many Trades"/> The band began touring again as planned, with a memorable exception in May 1993. Tool was scheduled to play the Garden Pavilion in [[Hollywood]], but learned at the last minute that the Garden Pavilion belonged to [[L. Ron Hubbard]]'s [[Church of Scientology]], which clashes with "the band's ethics about how a person should not follow a belief system that constricts their development as a human being."<ref name="Stepping Out From the Shadows" /> Keenan recalled that he "spent most of the show baa-ing like a sheep at the audience."<ref name="33 things">{{cite web | url=http://www.blender.com/guide/articles.aspx?id=2002 | title=33 Things You Should Know About Tool | work=Blender | accessdate=2006-09-18 | author=Jon Dolan | year=2006 | month=August }}</ref> 

After several successful concerts on the second stage during the [[Lollapalooza]] road show later that year, Tool was offered the chance to play on the main stage due to their "presence, prowess and power."<ref name="Stepping Out From the Shadows"/> On Lollapalooza's last night, a hometown concert in [[Los Angeles, California|Los Angeles]], Tool was introduced by [[Bill Hicks]], who had become a friend and important influence on the band after being mentioned in ''Undertow'''s liner notes.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://toolshed.down.net/articles/index.php?action=view-article&id=April_1997--High_Times.html | title=Hard rockers hail comic genius Bill Hicks. (transcript) | work=High Times | accessdate=2006-09-18 | author=Janiss Garza | year=1997 | month=April }}</ref> Due to the boost in popularity the band gained from these concerts, ''Undertow'' was certified [[RIAA certification|gold]] by the [[Recording Industry Association of America|RIAA]] that same year, despite being sold with a [[Corporate censorship|censored]], [[Defacement (vandalism)|defaced]] album cover by distributors like [[Wal-Mart]].<ref name="Axcess">{{cite web | last =Griffin | first =J.R. | title =TOOL on Videos, Censorship, Art, And Why You Should Never Let A G | work =Axcess | date =1994 | url =http://toolshed.down.net/articles/index.php?action=view-article&id=Sometime_1994--Axcess.html | accessdate =2007-05-13 | quote=It came as no surprise when Wal-Mart and KMart refused to carry the album. Rather than miss out on a large audience, Tool decided to censor itself and released a plain white album cover that contained nothing more than a giant bar code, the band's name, and the album tracks. }}</ref> The single "[[Sober (song)|Sober]]" continued to go strong as well, closing in on becoming a hit single by March 1994,<ref name="Jones a Master of Many Trades"/> and winning the band first awards for the accompanying music video, such as Billboard's "Best Video By A New Artist".<ref name="Jones a Master of Many Trades"/>

{{Sound sample box align left|Music sample:}}{{listen|filename=Tool - Undertow - Prison Sex - sample.ogg|title=Prison Sex excerpt|description="Prison Sex" was removed from the MTV playlist, because its video was deemed "too graphic and offensive."|format=[[Ogg]]}}{{Sample box end}}

With the release of Tool's follow-up to "Sober", "[[Prison Sex (Tool song)|Prison Sex]]", the band again became the target of censorship. Due to the symbolic portrayal of [[child abuse]], the American branch of [[MuchMusic]] called the band into question by deeming the respective music video &mdash; like "Sober" mainly created by guitarist Adam Jones &mdash; too graphic and offensive,<ref name="Stepping Out From the Shadows" /> and [[MTV]] stopped airing the video after a few viewings.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://toolshed.down.net/articles/text/sfc.nov.94.html | title=A Tool for the Truly Cool - Big hit of Lollapalooza tour gears up for second album | accessdate=2006-03-02 | year=1994 | work=San Francisco Chronicle}}</ref> Still, ''Undertow'' was certified platinum in September 1994.<ref>{{cite web | title =Tool Timeline | publisher =Rock On The Net | url =http://www.rockonthenet.com/artists-t/tool.htm | accessdate =2007-05-09}}</ref>

In September 1995, the band entered the studios to record their second album. At that time, Tool experienced its first and until today, only line-up change: bassist d'Amour left the band amicably. Chosen over tough competitors such as [[Kyuss]]' [[Scott Reeder]],<ref>{{cite web
| title = Sink or Swim - A Conversation With Tool's Justin Chancellor
| publisher = Gavin Magazin
| author = Rob Fiend
| month = October
| year = 1996
| url = http://toolshed.down.net/articles/index.php?action=view-article&id=October_1996--CMJ_New_Music_Report.html | accessdate =2007-05-09
}}</ref> [[Justin Chancellor]], a member of former tourmates [[Peach (band)|Peach]], eventually replaced d'Amour.<ref>{{cite web | title =Tool Bio: Justin Chancellor | publisher =Toolband.com | url =http://www.toolband.com/identity/justin/main.html | accessdate =2007-05-09 }}</ref>

===''<U+00C6>nima'' (1996<U+2013>2000)===
[[Image:Tool aenima cover dedication to hicks.jpg|thumb|200px|right|This version of the ''[[<U+00C6>nima]]'' artwork shows a dedication to satirist [[Bill Hicks]], "another dead hero."]]
After Justin Chancellor came on board, recording of the already-begun ''[[<U+00C6>nima]]'' continued. The band enlisted the help of producer [[David Bottrill]], who had produced some of [[King Crimson]]'s albums while Jones collaborated with [[Cam de Leon]] to create ''<U+00C6>nima'''s (later Grammy-nominated) artwork. The album was released in October 1996, and displayed influences of other artists as well:

[[Satire|Satirist]] [[Bill Hicks]] had long been an inspiration for the band and is noted as such in the liner notes of ''Undertow''. Two-and-a-half years prior to the release of ''<U+00C6>nima'' Bill Hicks died, and the album is dedicated to his memory.<ref name="Stepping Out From the Shadows"/> The band intended to raise awareness about Hicks' material and ideas, because they felt that they "were resonating similar concepts. Unity is the philosophical center. Evolution. Change."<ref name="austinkeenanhicks">{{cite web
| url =
http://toolshed.down.net/articles/index.php?action=view-article&id=May_1997--The_Austin_Chronicle.html
| title = Another Dead Hero
| author = Andy Langer
| work = The Austin Chronicle
| date = May, 1997
| accessdate = 2007-05-29
| quote = The late, Austin-based comedian gets big play on Aenima: several of his routines are sampled, there's a painting of him in the CD booklet titled Another Dead Hero, and the disc's back cover inlay depicts Hicks' California-in-the-ocean "Arizona Bay" theory. Keenan says Aenima is not a tribute to Hicks, he's fully aware what kind of exposure this highly anticipated album should give the late comedian. [...] "I think that's what he really liked about us as well -- that we were resonating similar concepts. Unity is the philosophical center. Evolution. Change. Internally and externally. Individually and globally. That's pretty much the gist of his comedy no matter what he was talking about -- music, porno, smoking." [...] Still, the most obvious connection are the Hicks' samples that end Aenima's title cut and segue into the album-closing, "Third Eye," a song about the government's war on drugs.
}}</ref> In particular, ''<U+00C6>nima'''s final track "Third Eye", a song about the U.S. Government's [[War on Drugs|war on drugs]], is preceded by a clip of Hicks' performances and both the [[lenticular]] casing of the ''<U+00C6>nima'' CD packaging as well as the chorus of the title track "[[<U+00C6>nema]]" make reference to Hick's idea of [[California]] falling into the [[Pacific Ocean]], stemming from a sketch about his hatred of [[Los Angeles, California|Los Angeles]], found on his album ''[[Arizona Bay]]''.<ref name="austinkeenanhicks"/><ref>{{cite web
| url = http://www.ucdadvocate.com/home/index.cfm?event=displayArticle&ustory_id=f13de017-3fd8-4f74-9abd-9f3f54482961
| title = Dead 10 years, Hicks still makes us laugh
| author = John Zwick
| work = [[University of Colorado at Denver]] Advocate
| date = [[2004-02-25]]
| accessdate = 2007-04-09
| quote = ...<U+00C6>nema referenced Bill's concept album, ''Arizona Bay'', envisioning a day when American culture would be purified by a cataclysmic earthquake sending California sinking into the sea.
}}</ref> Eventually, "<U+00C6>nema" would win Tool their first [[Grammy Award]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.rockonthenet.com/archive/1998/grammys.htm
| title = 40th Grammy Awards
| work = Rockonthenet.com
| year = 1998
| accessdate = 2007-05-26
}}</ref>

{{Sound sample box align left|Music sample:}}{{listen|filename=Tool - <U+00C6>nima - <U+00C6>nema - sample.ogg|title="<U+00C6>nema" excerpt|description=This Bill Hicks inspired song won the 1998 [[Grammy Award for Best Metal Performance]].|format=[[Ogg]]}}{{Sample box end}}

To support the album, the band released "[[Stinkfist]]" as a first single. Yet it had difficulty gaining airplay, and it was shortened by radio programmers. Additionally, MTV renamed the music video of "Stinkfist" to "Track #1" due to offensive connotations,<ref name="stinkfist" /> and the lyrics of the song were altered.<ref>{{cite book
| title = Nu-Metal: The Next Generation of Rock and Punk
| author = [[Joel McIver]]
| publisher = [[Omnibus Press]]
| date = [[2002-05-01]]
| isbn = 978-0711992092
| pages = 137
| accessdate = 2007-04-08
}}</ref> Responding to fan complaints of [[Censorship of music|censorship]], [[Matt Pinfield]], the host of MTV's ''120 Minutes'', expressed regrets by waving his fist in front of his face on air while explaining the reason for the name change as he introduced the video.<ref name="stinkfist" />

A tour began as well, in October 1996, only two weeks after ''<U+00C6>nima'''s release. Following numerous appearances in the United States and Europe, Tool headed for Australia in late March 1997. April 1 saw the first of several [[April Fools' Day|April Fools]] pranks related with the band, most of them being initiated by Kabir Akhtar, webmaster of the semi-official fanpage [http://toolshed.down.net t.d.n.], announcing that:
<blockquote>"...while on tour in Australia, Tool's tour bus was involved in a serious highway accident. Early reports from Zoo Entertainment are that at least three of the band are listed in critical condition."<ref name="tdn - april fools 97">{{cite web | url=http://toolshed.down.net/news/aprilfools97.html | title=Tool News: April Fools 1997 | accessdate=2007-03-29 | author=Kabir Akhtar}}</ref></blockquote>

The hoax gained wide attention, and was eventually exposed on radio and MTV.<ref name="tdn - april fools 97"/> Akhtar later posted an apology, claiming that t.d.n. "will not indulge itself in such outlandish pranks in the future"<ref name="tdn - april fools 97"/> - a false claim as later pranks would prove. Of course, the tour continued the next day as originally announced. Eventually returning to the United States, Tool appeared at [[Lollapalooza]] '97 in July, this time as a headliner, gaining critical praise from ''[[The New York Times]]'':
<blockquote>"Tool was returning in triumph to Lollapalooza after appearing among the obscure bands on the festival's smaller stage in 1993. Now Tool is the prime attraction for a festival that's struggling to maintain its purpose. [...] Tool uses taboo-breaking imagery for hellfire moralizing in songs that swerve from bitter reproach to nihilistic condemnation. Its music has refined all the troubled majesty of grunge."<ref name="nytimeslollapalooza">{{cite web | url=http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9903EEDF1738F937A25754C0A961958260 | title=Lollapalooza's Recycled Hormones: Rebellion by the Numbers | work=The New York Times | accessdate=2006-03-06 | author=Jon Pareles}}</ref></blockquote>

''<U+00C6>nima'' proved to be able to match Tool's successful debut, selling equal numbers,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://toolshed.down.net/articles/index.php?action=view-article&id=August_1997--Circus.html | date= August, 1997 | title=Never Wanted To Be Rock Stars But They Are (transcript) | work=Circus | accessdate=2006-06-25 | author=Edward Fruchtman | quote =Both albums (Aenima and 1993s Undertow) have already exceeded a million in sales and their first release, [...] }}</ref> featuring the Grammy-awarded "[[<U+00C6>nema]]", and appearing on "Best Albums of 1996" lists as in ''[[Kerrang!]]''.<ref name="acclaimedaenima">{{cite web
| url=http://www.acclaimedmusic.net/061024/A3618.htm
| title=Tool - Aenima
| work=acclaimedmusic.net
| accessdate=2007-06-25
}}</ref> Still, a legal battle had begun that same year that would impede the band from working on another release. [[Volcano Records]] &mdash; the successor of Tool's by-then defunct label Zoo Entertainment &mdash; alleged contract violations by Tool and filed [[lawsuit|suit]]. Tool looked at offers from other record labels, an action not allowed by the contract, according to Volcano. After Tool filed a [[Lawsuit|counter suit]] stating that Volcano failed to use a renewal option in their contract, the parties settled out of court. The parties later agreed to a new contract and a three-record deal.<ref>{{cite web
| url=http://toolshed.down.net/faq/faq.html
| title=C15
| work=The Tool FAQ
| accessdate=2007-06-04
| author=Kabir Akhtar
| quote = In late 1997, Volcano Records filed suit against Tool, claiming the band had violated their contract by seeking / entertaining offers from other labels. Tool filed suit against Volcano, saying that the label had failed to exercise a renewal option in their contract, and so they were free to leave. This ugly deadlock lasted for over a year, when finally, at the last minute, both parties agreed to terms (including a three-record deal), rather than going to court.
}}</ref> This legal battle put a great strain on the band and delayed work on their next album.<ref name="Stepping Out From the Shadows"/> During this time, Keenan founded a new band, [[A Perfect Circle]], with long-time Tool guitar tech [[Billy Howerdel]] and members of other well known bands such as [[Jeordie White|Marilyn Manson]], [[Tim Alexander|Primus]], [[Troy Van Leeuwen|Failure]], [[James Iha|The Smashing Pumpkins]] and [[Josh Freese|The Vandals]].

At this point, rumors that Tool were breaking up began to spread,<ref>{{cite web
| url = http://www.statenews.com/article.phtml?pk=13061
| title = Breslin hosts heavier sound
| author = Scott Kline
| work = [[The State News]]
| date = [[2002-10-17]]
| accessdate = 2007-04-09
| quote = Rumors of a breakup surfaced when Maynard joined former Tool guitar tech Billy Howderdel as a part of A Perfect Circle.
}}</ref><ref name="FresnoBee">{{cite web
| url = http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-94564619.html
| title = Tool tops weekend menu.
| author = Mike Osegueda
| work = [[The Fresno Bee]]
| date = [[2002-11-22]]
| accessdate = 2007-04-09
| quote = If there's something Tool is known for besides the music, it's the mysterious vibe the group gives off. Rumors about a breakup had circulated for a while before their last album. Tool usually includes odd artwork in CDs.
}}</ref> until the band released the ''[[Salival]]'' [[box set]] ([[Compact Disc|CD]]/[[VHS]] or CD/[[DVD]]) in 2000, effectively putting an end to the rumors.<ref name="AllMusic Biography" /> The CD contained one new original track, a [[Cover version|cover]] of Led Zeppelin's "[[No Quarter (song)|No Quarter]]," a live cover of Peach's "[[You Lied]]," and live recordings of old songs arranged differently from their studio counterparts.<ref>{{cite web
| url = http://www.bgnews.com/home/index.cfm?event=displayArticlePrinterFriendly&uStory_id=56b4ca95-a0e5-47de-9c73-b4947d95476c
| title = Tool's latest worth salivating over
| author = Matt Hayes
| work = BG News
| date = [[2001-02-16]]
| accessdate = 2007-04-09
| quote = ...the majority of the tunes contain surprisingly different arrangements from the studio originals.
}}</ref> The VHS and DVD both contained four music videos, with a bonus music video for "Hush" on the DVD. Although ''Salival'' did not produce any singles, the hidden track "Maynard's Dick" (which dates back to the ''Opiate'' era) briefly found its way to [[FM broadcasting|FM radio]] when several DJs chose to play it on air under the title "Maynard's Dead".<ref>{{cite web
| url=http://toolshed.down.net/faq/faq.html
| title=H26
| work=The Tool FAQ
| accessdate=2007-05-12
| author=Kabir Akhtar
| quote = Many radio stations began playing it as soon as they got their hands on it, and started calling it "Maynard's Dead" - most likely because they cannot say its real title on the air. But it is about, and it is titled, "Maynard's Dick." As you can probably tell by the more-thrash-than-usual style, "Maynard's Dick" is actually not a "new" song. It was rumored to exist for a long time, since the "Opiate" days, but only surfaced on this CD.
}}</ref>

===''Lateralus'' (2001-2005)===
In January 2001, Tool announced a new album, ''Systema Enc<U+00E9>phale'', along with a 12-song tracklist full of esoteric and obscure words such as "Riverchrist," "Numbereft," "Encephatalis," "Musick," and "Coeliacus."<ref name="tdnsystematracks">{{cite web | url=http://toolshed.down.net/news/oldnews/old0101.html | title=January - march 2001 | work=news archive | accessdate=2006-03-06 | author=Kabir Akhtar | quote=[[01/12/01]] - Yesterday, the Official Site reported a title and tracklist for the new album. The album is apparently called "Systema Enc<U+00E9>phale" and features 12 tracks: "Malfeasance, U.V.R., Numbereft, Encephatalis, Musick, Coeliacus, Pain Canal, Lactation, Smyrma, Riverchrist." Whether this is real, or another "we read the Joyful Guide to Lachrymology while recording <U+00C6>nima in eight days in France", is not yet clear. [...] [03/29/01] Sadly, yes, there are a whole lot of fake Tool songs out there on Napster now. I have no idea which they are, and keeping a list here would really take far too much time to be worth it. }}</ref> As anticipated, file-sharing engines such as [[Napster]] became flooded with bogus files disguised with those titles.<ref name="tdnsystematracks"/> During that time, Tool members were outspokenly critical of engines like Napster due to the negative impact on smaller artists that are dependent on success in record sales to continue their career. Keenan had this to say during an interview with ''NY Rock'' in 2000:

<blockquote>"I think there are a lot of other industries out there that might deserve being destroyed. The ones who get hurt by [[MP3]]s are not so much companies or the business, but the artists, people who are trying to write songs."<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.nyrock.com/interviews/2000/apc_int.asp | title=Interview with Maynard James Keenan of A Perfect Circle | work=NY Rock | accessdate=2006-04-28 | author=Gabriella}}</ref></blockquote>

{{Sound sample box align left|Music sample:}}{{listen|filename=Tool - Lateralus - Parabola - sample.ogg|title="Parabola" excerpt|description="Parabola" exists on ''Lateralus'' as two separate tracks, "Parabol" and "Parabola." This excerpt sets off at the beginning of the latter.|format=[[Ogg]]}}{{Sample box end}}
Only one month later, they revealed that the new album was actually titled ''[[Lateralus]]'' and that the name ''Systema Enc<U+00E9>phale'' and the tracklist had been a ruse,<ref name="mtvnewssystema">{{cite web | url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1439483/02152001/tool.jhtml | title=Tool Tinker With Album Title, Set Track List | work=MTV News | accessdate=2006-03-06 | author=Joe D'Angelo}}</ref> much to the dismay of music magazines and commercial websites who had committed headlong to the fake title. ''Lateralus'' took Tool a step further down into [[Art rock|art]]-<ref name="e!onlinelateralus">{{cite web
| url=http://web.archive.org/web/20031218003654/http://www.eonline.com/Reviews/Facts/Music/RevID/0,1107,2309,00.html
 | title=Lateralus review | work=E! Online | year=2001 | accessdate=2007-06-18 | author=E! Online | quote= This monstrous art-rock band has ignored pretty much every musical trend, cautiously releasing just three full-length albums over the span of a decade and getting progressively weirder (and garnering more respect) with each one. Lateralus takes the L.A. band over the edge
 [...] }}</ref> and [[progressive rock]]<ref name="rollingstonelateralus"/> territory &mdash; the ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' wrote in an attempt to summarize the album: "Drums, bass and guitars move in jarring cycles of hyperhowl and near-silent [[death march]]. [...] The prolonged running times of most of Lateralus' thirteen tracks are misleading; the entire album rolls and stomps with [[suite]]like purpose."<ref name="rollingstonelateralus"/> Close to 79 minutes in length, ''Lateralus'''s relatively complex and long songs &mdash; topped by the music video for "[[Parabola (song)|Parabola]]" with ten-and-a-half minutes &mdash; still posed a challenge to fans and music programming alike.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.avclub.com/content/node/12709 | title=Lateralus review | work=The A.V. Club | date=[[March 29]], 2002 | accessdate=2007-05-25 | author=Joshua Klein| quote=
Tool heartily embraces prog epics, daring fans to hold on and radio stations to sacrifice their precious airtime to tracks that push 10 minutes [...] }}</ref>

Nevertheless, the album became a success the world over, reaching #1 on the U.S. [[Billboard 200]] albums chart in its debut week.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://billboard.com/bbcom/discography/index.jsp?pid=19952&aid=473403 | title=Discography Tool Laterlaus | work=Billboard.com | accessdate=2006-04-29 | author=Billboard.com}}</ref> Tool received their second Grammy Award for the best metal performance of 2001 for the song "Schism."<ref>{{cite web
| url = http://www.grammy.com/GRAMMY_Awards/Winners/
| title = Grammy Award Winners
| publisher = [[The Recording Academy]]
| accessdate = 2007-04-28
}}</ref> During the band's acceptance speech, drummer Carey stated that he would like to thank his parents (for putting up with him) and [[Satan]], while bassist Chancellor concluded: "I want to thank my dad for doing my mom."<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1452651/02272002/u2.jhtml | title=Alicia Keys Takes Five, 'O Brother' Gets Most At 44th Grammy Awards | work=MTV.com | accessdate=2006-08-07 | year=2002 | author=Joe D'Angelo}}</ref>

[[Image:Tool KingCrimson Poster.jpg|thumb|200px|right|In 2001, progressive rock pioneers [[King Crimson]] opened 10 concerts during Tool's tour to promote ''Lateralus''.]]
Extensive touring throughout 2001 and 2002 supported ''Lateralus'', and included a personal highlight of the band: a 10-show mini-tour with King Crimson in August 2001, during which the progressive rock veterans opened for Tool. During a show at the [[Red Rocks Amphitheatre]] Keenan concluded: "For me, being on stage with King Crimson is like [[Lenny Kravitz]] playing with [[Led Zeppelin]], or [[Britney Spears]] onstage with [[Debbie Gibson]]."<ref name="kingcrimsonminitour">{{cite web | url=http://toolshed.down.net/articles/index.php?action=view-article&id=August_2001--MTV_Online.html | title=Tool Stretch Out And Slow Down In Show With King Crimson | work=MTV.com | accessdate=2007-03-23 | year=2001 | author=Laura Bond}}</ref> The tour eventually came to an end on [[November 24]] [[2002]] in [[Long Beach, California]] at [http://www.longbeachcc.com/arena.htm Long Beach Arena].

Although the end of the tour seemed to spell another dormancy for the band, they did not become completely inactive. While Keenan recorded and toured with [[A Perfect Circle]], the other band members released an official yet fanclub exclusive interview and a recording of new material. On [[March 31]], [[2005]], the official website announced - to the shock of many fans and friends - that "Maynard has found Jesus" and would be abandoning the recording of the new Tool album temporarily and possibly permanently. [[Kurt Loder]] of [[MTV]] contacted Keenan via email to ask for a confirmation and received a very nonchalant confirmation. When Loder asked again, Keenan's response was simply "heh heh."<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1499613/20050405/tool.jhtml?headlines=true
| title = Maynard And Jesus Split: The Conclusion | author = Chris Harris
| publisher = [[MTV News]] | date = [[2005-04-07]] | accessdate = 2007-02-14}}</ref> On April 7, the official Tool site posted the following news item titled with the [[Bill Hicks]] quote "Christians, huh? So forgive me.": "Good news, [[April fool]]s fans. The writing and recording is back under way."<ref>{{cite web | url=http://web.archive.org/web/20051024134948/toolband.com/news/ | title=Tool: News | work=toolband.com | accessdate=2007-03-30 | year=2005 | author=Blair MacKenzie Blake}}</ref>

While the writing and recording proceeded for the by then long awaited follow-up to ''Lateralus'', the wait was shortened by the release of a ''Lateralus'' vinyl edition, two DVD singles, and a new elaborate splash intro to the band's official website by artist [[Joshua Davis (web designer)|Joshua Davis]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Joshua Davis - Projects - Web - Tool|url=http://www.joshuadavis.com/|format=FLASH|accessdate=2007-04-02}}</ref> The "double [[Gramophone record|vinyl]] four-picture disc" edition of ''Lateralus'' was first released as a limited autographed edition exclusively available to fan-club members, and publicly released on [[August 23]] [[2005]]. On [[December 20]] [[2005]], the two [[DVD]]s were released, one containing the single "[[Schism (song)|Schism]]" and the other "[[Parabola (song)|Parabola]]",<ref name="AMG Schism DVD review">{{cite web | url=http://www.allmusic.com/cg/amg.dll?p=amg&sql=10:j9fyxqqdldje | year=2005| title=Schism DVD review | work=AllMusic | accessdate=2007-05-25 | author=Rob Theakston}}</ref><ref name="AMG Parabola DVD review">{{cite web | url=http://www.allmusic.com/cg/amg.dll?p=amg&sql=10:39foxqqdldae | year=2005| title=Parabola DVD review | work=AllMusic | accessdate=2007-05-25 | author=Rob Theakston}}</ref> a remix by [[Lustmord]],<ref name="AMG Schism DVD review"/><ref name="AMG Parabola DVD review"/> and the music video with commentary by [[David Yow]] and [[Jello Biafra]], respectively.<ref name="AMG Schism DVD review"/><ref name="AMG Parabola DVD review"/>

=== ''10,000 Days'' (2006-present) ===
By then fifteen years into the band's career, Tool had acquired a devoted, "[[Cult following|cult]]" following,<ref name="revolver">{{Citation
 | last = Epstein
 | first = Dan
 | title = Do What You Wilt
 | journal = Revolver
 | volume =
 | issue = April
 | pages =
 | date = April 28, 2006
 | year = 2006
}}</ref> and as the first minor details about the band's next album emerged, such as the influence of ''Lateralus'' tourmates [[Fant<U+00F4>mas (band)|Fant<U+00F4>mas]] and [[Meshuggah]],<ref name="mtvhammer">{{cite web | url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1486242/20040407/story.jhtml | title=Tool Hammer Away At New Album | work=MTV News | accessdate=2006-04-06 | author=Jon Wiederhorn}}</ref> the notorious rumor mill surrounding new Tool-releases resurfaced. One of the main controversies regarding the new release was the album title. After rumored titles such as ''Teleincision'' had been dismissed, a news item on the official Tool website eventually announced the new album's name on [[March 3]], [[2006]]: ''[[10,000 Days]]''.<ref>{{cite web | title =TOOL: New Album Title Revealed? | publisher =Blabbermouth.net | date =Mar. 3, 2006 | url =http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=49079 | accessdate =2007-05-09 }}</ref>

Still, the rumors surrounding the band's activities reached a point where it was speculated that they had fabricated a "decoy" album to fool audiences until the day of release,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.theage.com.au/news/music/is-anyone-listening/2006/05/03/1146335806864.html | title="Is anyone listening?" | work="The Age" | accessdate=2006-05-06 | year=2006|author="Patrick Donovan"}}</ref> but this began to subside when a [[internet leak|leaked]] copy of the album was illegally distributed via [[filesharing]] networks a week prior to the official release.<ref>{{cite web
| title =Tool Planning Summer Tour Around Keenan's Wine Harvest
| publisher =VH1.com
| date =May 11, 2006
| url =http://www.vh1.com/news/articles/1531583/20060511/tool.jhtml
| accessdate =2007-06-15
| author= Chris Harris
| quote=There was some doubt that the disc would sell as much as it did, Chancellor said, given the album leaked to the Internet the week before it was released. "You never quite know," he said. "We were really bummed out about [the album leaking]. We took a lot of precautions to stop that from happening. [...] We sort of expected it, and we were pretty much pleased that it managed to last that long without getting out there, and even happier people wanted to go out and buy it anyway."
}}</ref> The album opener "[[Vicarious (Tool song)|Vicarious]]" premiered on US radio stations on April 17, while the record was released as announced on [[May 2]] [[2006]] in the US, and debuted at the top spots of various international charts. ''10,000 Days'' sold 564,000 copies in its opening week in the US, reaching number one on the [[Billboard 200]] charts, doubling sales of [[Pearl Jam]]'s self-titled album, the closest competitor.<ref>{{cite web | title=Tool, Pearl Jam Claim Billboard Chart In The Name Of Rock (May 10, 2006) | url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1531452/05102006/tool.jhtml|accessdate=2006-09-17}}</ref> However, the critical reception of ''10,000 Days'' was less favourable than its predecessor ''[[Lateralus]]'' (as indicated by a [[Metacritic]] average score of 68<ref>{{cite web | year= 2006 | url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/artists/tool/10000days?q=tool | title=Tool: 10,000 Days (2006): Reviews | accessdate=2006-09-17 }}</ref> compared to 75).<ref>{{cite web | year= 2001 | url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/artists/tool/lateralus?q=tool | title=Tool: Lateralus (2001): Reviews | accessdate=2007-06-17 }}</ref>

[[Image:Tool roskilde festival 2006.jpg|300px|thumb|right|Tool appeared at many big festivals during their ''10,000 Days'' tour. Here, they play the orange stage (main stage) at the 2006 edition of [[Roskilde Festival]].]]
After the release of ''10,000 Days'', a tour kicked off at [[Coachella Valley Music and Arts Festival|Coachella]] on [[April 30]], [[2006]]. Much like the ''Lateralus'' tour of 2001, it was followed by a handful of shows in smaller venues and theaters in the U.S. and Canada,<ref>{{cite web | year=2006 | url=http://toolshed.down.net/tour/spring06/ | title=spring 2006 | work=The Tool Page: Tour Info | accessdate=2007-05-12 }}</ref> and then festivals, such as the [[Download Festival]], [[Rock am Ring]] and [[Pinkpop]], and solo shows in Europe.<ref>{{cite web | year=2006 | url=http://toolshed.down.net/tour/summer06/ | title=summer 2006 | work=The Tool Page: Tour Info | accessdate=2007-05-12 }}</ref> In fall 2006, Tool toured across North America, playing in large arenas and amphitheatres with support by [[Isis (band)|Isis]].<ref name="tourfall2006">{{cite web | year=2006 | url=http://toolshed.down.net/tour/fall06/ | title=fall 2006 | work=The Tool Page: Tour Info | accessdate=2007-05-12 }}</ref> From November to mid-December, they returned to Europe to present the stage show in cities not covered by the first leg, this time with [[Mastodon (band)|Mastodon]] as the opening act.<ref name="tourfall2006"/> After touring [[Australia]] and [[New Zealand]] to headline the [[Big Day Out]] music festivals, with sideshows in Sydney and Melbourne, Tool's plan to continue to North America until April were postponed to June due to a [[bicep]] tear suffered by Danny Carey during a short break from touring. Early speculation caused by Tool's website was that he was injured in a fight with a boxer.<ref>{{cite web | year= 2007 | url=http://www.toolband.com/news/index.html | title=TOOL : NEWS | accessdate=2007-05-10 }}</ref> However, it was later clear that the boxer was a dog.<ref>{{cite web | year=2007 | url=http://www.elpasotimes.com/entertainment/ci_5810921 | title=El Paso Times - Tool: On the road after timeout for dog-related injury | accessdate=2007-05-10}}</ref> Carey underwent surgery on [[February 21]]. Nevertheless, the band's gig at the [[Bonnaroo Music Festival]] 2007 in Tennessee was never in jeopardy<ref>{{cite web | last =Kilgore | first =Kym | title =Tool extends tour through mid-July | work =LiveDaily | date =May 04, 2007 | url =http://www.livedaily.com/news/Tool_extends_tour_through_midJuly-12052.html?t=12 | accessdate =2007-05-10 }}</ref> &mdash; on [[June 16]], Tool appeared as a headliner surprising the audience with the guest appearance of [[Rage Against the Machine]]'s [[Tom Morello]] on "Lateralus".<ref>{{cite web | author =Jonathan Cohen | title =Tool, All-Star Zeppelin Jam Highlight Bonnaroo Day One | work =Billboard.com | date = June 16, 2007 | url =http://www.billboard.com/bbcom/news/article_display.jsp?vnu_content_id=1003599898 | accessdate =2007-06-17 }}</ref>

In the meanwhile, the elaborate packaging of ''10,000 Days'' gained Tool the distinction of "Best Recording Package" during the 49th Grammy Awards in February 2007, but their first single "Vicarious" fell short in the category "Best Hard Rock Performance" to [[Wolfmother]]'s "Woman".<ref name="49thgrammyawards">{{cite web | url=http://www.grammy.com/GRAMMY_Awards/49th_Show/list.aspx | title="Awards Winners List" | work="49th Annual Grammy Awards" | accessdate=2007-03-25 | year=2007|author="Grammy.com"}}</ref>

In regard to the band's future, Justin Chancellor said in a recent interview that the band would be continuing their tour probably until early 2008, and then, take "some proper time off".<ref name="justinnwlanews">{{cite web | last =Pulsifer| first =Eric | title =Tool returns to Bossier on Thursday | work =nwlanews.com | date =15 May, 2007 | url = http://www.nwlanews.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=4170&Itemid=56 | accessdate =2007-06-07 | quote = the future of tool:
We really do not know. We're guessing we will probably be done around January or February next year and at that point we will defitinely (sic) take some time off, I mean you know some proper time off from each other. Whether it's six months or a year I do not know, but at that point then we will decide what we will do next. [...] a new album: There's a big stockpile of things that we have not really created into songs yet so there's lots to do. I'm sure if everyone is still good at the end of this and we do not damage ourselves too much then I'm sure there'll be another album, but I cannot say when. }}</ref> He qualified this by adding that the band has already written new material and will surely release another album at some point down the road.<ref name="justinnwlanews"/> One of the rumored projects until a possible next album is to make a "band movie",<ref name=billboardmovie>{{cite web
| title =Tool movie in the works?
| publisher =billboard.com
| date = June 12, 2007
| url =http://www.billboard.com/bbcom/news/article_display.jsp?vnu_content_id=1003597438
| accessdate =2007-06-15
| author= John Benson
| quote=Adam Jones tells Billboard.com the alt-metal act is tossing around ideas for a band movie. [...] Jones [...] says movie discussion is nothing new to the Los Angeles-based band. If the right financial backer entered the picture, it could become a reality sooner than later. [...] "If I had my way, it would be a narrative story in a surreal fashion with as much money and special effects we could throw at it. I think some of the other guys would like to do pockets of all of that or something that's live or we're playing. It's just talk right now."
}}</ref> a possibility the band has reportedly thought of for a long time.<ref name=billboardmovie/> The ideas range from "a narrative story in a surreal fashion with as much money and special effects" as possible to "pockets of all of that or something that's live or the band playing."<ref name=billboardmovie/> And although Carey stated that the necessary know-how was at hand due to the many relations to artists working in the movie business,<ref>{{cite web
| title =Tool movie in the works?
| publisher =The Rock Radio
| date = June 13, 2007
| url =http://www.therockradio.com/2007/06/tool-movie-in-works.html
| accessdate =2007-06-15
| author= The Rock Radio online
| quote=Tool drummer Danny Carey told us that the band has already assembled a team of film production people who work on their videos and could easily get involved in a full-fledged film."
}}</ref> Jones dismissed: "It's just talk right now."<ref name=billboardmovie/>

==Musical traits, genre and influences==
Tool has gained appreciation and critical praise for a complex and ever-evolving sound,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.asahi.com/english/Herald-asahi/TKY200701120170.html | date=January 12, 2007 | title=In Sight/Music & Arts Tool frontman: 'I have not smashed up 1 hotel room' | work=International Herald Tribune/The Asahi Shimbun | accessdate=2007-05-25|author=C.B. Liddell | quote=The Tool sound that evolved between its grungy heavy metal debut, 1992s "Opiate" EP, and the band's 2001 breakthrough album, "Lateralus," is showcased on the current release. "10,000 Days" includes lengthy compositions with complex musical structures that eschew obvious hooks and verse--chorus-- verse repetitiveness. This creates songs that sound rambling and even jazzy in form [...]}}</ref> which complicates classifying the band and narrowing down their musical origins. Many illustrious examples describe their sound, such as "grinding, post-[[Jane's Addiction]] heavy metal"<ref name="AllMusic Biography"/> and "[[Led Zeppelin]]'s heaving, battering guitar riffs and Middle Eastern modes".<ref>{{cite web | url=http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9903EEDF1738F937A25754C0A961958260 | year=1997 | title=Lollapalooza's Recycled Hormones: Rebellion by the Numbers | work=The New York Times | accessdate=2006-04-28|author=Jon Pareles}}</ref> Additionally, they have been explained as a "blend of vintage Jane's Addiction and [[King Crimson]]"<ref name="rollingstonelateralus"/> and [[Pink Floyd]]'s ''Meddle'' (1971), but thirty years later and altered by "Tool's impulse to cram every inch of infinity with hard guitar meat and absolute dread".<ref name="AMG Lateralus review"/> The band cites its influences as King Crimson,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.toolband.com/news/letter/2001_09.php | year=2001| title=Augustember 2001 E.V. | work=Tool Newsletter | accessdate=2006-04-28 | author=Blair Blake}}</ref> [[The Melvins]],<ref>{{cite web | url=http://toolshed.down.net/articles/index.php?action=view-article&id=March_1997--Alternative_Press.html | year=1997 | title=Nobody's Tool | work=Alternative Press | accessdate=2007-04-08 | author=Jason Pettigrew}}</ref> and [[Meshuggah]].<ref name="mtvhammer"/>

===Musical traits===
An essential component of Tool's song repertoire relies on the heavy use of odd meter [[time signature]]s. For instance, bassist Justin Chancellor describes the time signature employed on ''[[Lateralus|Lateralus']]'' first single "[[Schism (song)|Schism]]", as 6.5/8 and that it later "goes into all kinds of other times".<ref name="bassplayer052001">{{cite journal |last=Scott Shiraki & E.E. Bradman |first= |year=2001 |month=05 |title=Handy Man: How Justin Chancellor Frames Tool's Metal Madness |journal=Bass Player |url=http://www.basswriter.com/journalism/bpstories/Web-Chancellor.doc |accessdate=2007-05-02 |quote= }}</ref> The album's title track "[[Lateralus (song)|Lateralus]]" also displays shifting rhythms,<ref name="bassplayer052001"/> as does ''[[10,000 Days|10,000 Days']]'' (2006) "Wings for Marie (Pt 1)" and "10,000 Days (Wings Pt 2)".<ref name="moderndrummer072006">{{cite journal |last=Micallef |first=Ken |year=2006 |month=07 |title=10,000 Days... and beyond |journal=Modern Drummer |url= |accessdate=2007-05-02 |quote= }}</ref>

Beyond this fundamental aspect of the band's sound, each band member experiments within their musical scope. In general, Chancellor's bass playing is characterized by "thick midrange tone, guitar-style techniques, and elastic versatility".<ref name="bassplayer052001"/> An example of this is the use of a [[Wah-wah|wah effect]] by [[Hammer-on|hammering]] "the notes with the left hand and using the bass's tone controls to get a tone sweep", such as on the song "The Patient" (''Lateralus'' 2001).<ref name="bassplayer052001"/>

The band's drummer, Danny Carey, gained fame within the drum world for his use of [[tabla]]-style techniques, [[polyrhythm]]s, and the incorporation of custom [[Electronic drum|electronic drum pads]] to trigger samples, such as prerecorded [[octoban]] drum patterns.<ref name="moderndrummer072006"/>

Maynard James Keenan's contribution to Tool's sound has been characterized more subjectively. Specific accolades attested him a "distinct and soft but powerful" singing voice (''Undertow'' 1993)<ref>{{cite web | url=
http://media.www.westerncourier.com/media/storage/paper650/news/2005/12/09/TheEdge/Flashback-1126284.shtml | date=December 9, 2005 | title=Flashback - Tool "Undertow" | work=The Western Courier | accessdate=2007-05-25 | author=Khaled Okla}}</ref> or being able to perform as "a natural fit at replacing [[Layne Staley]]" during an [[Alice in Chains]] reunion concert in 2005.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://seattlepi.nwsource.com/pop/212872_alice21q.html | date=February 21, 2005 | title=Alice in Chains owns stage in tsunami-relief show full of surprises | work=Seattle Post-Intelligencer | accessdate=2007-05-25 | author=Travis Hay}}</ref> More generally, ''The New York Times'' said in regard to his role in his bands that A Perfect Circle and Tool "rely on Mr. Keenan's ability to dignify emotions like lust, anger and disgust, the honey in his voice adding a touch of profundity."<ref name="nytimeskeenan">{{cite web | url=
http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9C03E1D6113EF931A1575BC0A9669C8B63 | year=2002 | title=Self-Confidence, and a Tattoo | work=The New York Times | accessdate=2007-05-02 | author=Ann Powers}}</ref>

Guitarist Adam Jones is not known for dominating any particular guitar playing technique, but rather combines many techniques<ref name="guitarplayer2001">{{cite web | url= http://toolshed.down.net/articles/index.php?action=view-article&id=June_2001--Guitar_Player.html
| year=2001 | title=Mysterious Ways | month= June | work=Guitar Player | accessdate=2007-05-02
| author=Jon Wiederhorn | quote=Jones is not a shredder, a pop guitarist, a jazz man, an avant-garde
iconoclast, or a blues player, but his performances often include
elements from all those genres.}}</ref> such as "alternately utilizing power chords, scratchy noise, chiming arpeggios, and a quiet minimalism".<ref name="soberamgreview">{{cite web | url=http://www.allmusic.com/cg/amg.dll?p=amg&sql=33:wxfexqrrldae | year=| title=Sober Song Review | work=AllMusic.com | accessdate=2007-05-02 | author=Steve Huey}}</ref> Other techniques used by the band to expand their sound repertoire require forms of instrumental experimentation, for example, the use of a "pipe bomb microphone" (a guitar pickup mounted inside a brass cylinder), and a talk box guitar solo on "Jambi".<ref>{{cite web | last =Forlenza | first =Jeff | title =The Making of Tool's "10,000 Days" | publisher =Mix | date =Jul 1, 2006 | url =http://mixonline.com/recording/projects/audio_making_tools_days/ | accessdate =2007-05-09 }}</ref>

The band puts an emphasis on the sound of their songs and attempt to reduce the effect lyrics can have on the perception of songs by not releasing song lyrics with any album.<ref name="livewire"/> In some instances, their song lyrics are arranged in extraordinary manner, such as in "Lateralus". The number of syllables per word in the lyrics to "Lateralus" correspond to an arrangement of the [[fibonacci number]]s<ref name="diCarlointerview">{{cite web | author = Christopher W. diCarlo | title = Interview with Maynard James Keenan | url=http://www.cdicarlo.com/paper_04maynard.htm | accessdate = 2007-05-04 }}</ref> and in "Jambi" the metrical foot [[iamb]] is used.<ref name="julynewsletter">{{cite web | author = "Blair MacKenzie Blake" | title = Tool Newsletter, July 2006 | url=http://www.toolband.com/news/letter/2006_07.php | accessdate = 2006-08-03 }}</ref> The themes of their lyrics often include philosophical and spiritual issues &mdash; specific subjects range from [[evolution]] and [[Jungian]] psychology in "[[Forty-Six & 2]]", to organized [[religion]] in "Opiate" and [[Transcendence (philosophy)|transcendence]] in "[[Lateralus (song)|Lateralus]]". Keenan often explores issues very personal to him, such as the album name ''10,000 Days'' and the album's title track, which refer to the time Keenan's mother had to suffer from complications of a stroke until her passing away in 2003.<ref name="rs10kdaysreview">{{cite web | author = Evan Serpick | work= Rolling Stone | title = 10,000 Days Review | url=http://www.rollingstone.com/artists/tool/albums/album/10468655/review/10500551/10000_days | year= 2006 | accessdate = 2007-05-04 }}</ref>

===Genre allusions===
The band is often described using [[umbrella term]]s and critics often place them in many different [[Musical genre|genres]] at the same time.<ref>{{cite web | url =http://www.villagevoice.com/music/0638,sally,74479,22.html | title =Tool: An Appreciation | author =Zak Sally | work =The Village Voice | date =[[September 15]], 2006 | accessdate = 2007-05-09 | quote = ...they have transcended whatever genre label they are tagged with<U+2014>they aren't quite "metal," "prog" does not cut the mustard, "hard rock" is too vague, and "pop" is just plain wrong, although all those elements are in the mix. }}</ref> While seemingly contradictory, this is merely the result of "music genre" being "an ill-defined notion, that is not founded on any [[intrinsic and extrinsic properties|intrinsic property]] of the music, but rather depends on cultural [[intrinsic and extrinsic properties|extrinsic]] habits",<ref>{{Citation
 | last1 = Aucouturier | first1 = Jean-Julien
 | author1-link = Jean-Julien Aucouturier
 | last2 = Pachet| first2 = Fran<U+00E7>ois
 | author2-link = Fran<U+00E7>ois Pachet
 | title = Representing Musical Genre:A State of the Art
 | journal = Journal of New Music Research
 | volume = 32
 | issue = 1
 | pages = 83-93
 | year = 2003
 | url = http://www.idiap.ch/~paiement/references/to_read/music/genre_classification/pachet-02c.pdf
 | id = ISSN 0929-8215 }}</ref> such as [[Fads and trends|fads]] or simply personal [[Taste (sociology)|taste]].

Specifically, Tool "slipped into the definition of [[alternative rock]] during the post-Nirvana era" when playing Lollapalooza in 1993.<ref name="AllMusic Biography"/> At that time, their first full length album ''[[Undertow (Tool album)|Undertow]]'' had just been released. An increase in complexity and layering followed on their next album ''[[<U+00C6>nima]]'', (1996) which landed them in the [[alternative metal]] genre.<ref name="AllMusic Biography"/><ref name="rollingstoneaenima"/> They were also referred to as [[post-metal]],<ref name="post-metal1">{{cite news
| url = http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=ST&s_site=dfw&p_multi=ST&p_theme=realcities&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EAF8F12C40B57C7&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D
| title = At the main stage...
| author = Dave Ferman
| publisher = [[Fort Worth Star-Telegram]], archived by NewsBank
| date = [[1993-07-30]]
| accessdate = 2007-05-09
| format = fee required
| quote = Tool's vicious, post-metal attack is one of the more intense offerings of the day...
}}</ref><ref name="post-metal2">{{cite news
| url = http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117905701.html?categoryid=34&cs=1
| title = Live Performances: Tool
| author = Troy J. Augusto
| publisher = [[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]
| date = [[1996-10-16]]
| accessdate = 2007-05-09
| quote = The group's rhythm section, featuring new bassist Justin Chancellor, propelled the group's post-metal stylings with a twisted, near-jazz approach.
}}</ref> although this term did not come into wide use until the next decade.<ref>{{cite web
| author = Ed Thompson
| url = http://uk.music.ign.com/articles/747/747458p1.html
| title = ''In the Absence of Truth'' Review
| publisher = [[IGN]]
| date = 2006-11-22
| accessdate = 2007-05-09
| quote = ...many credit &#91;[[Isis (band)|Isis]]&#93; with being the inspiration of the term post-metal after the release of their 2002 album Oceanic...
}}</ref>

The band's next evolution involved more musical and visual art experimentation. Representing this is ''[[Lateralus|Lateralus']]'' elaborate album packaging and their complex live shows during the supporting tour, which sparked the use of the terms [[art rock]]<ref name="AllMusic Biography"/><ref name="kingcrimsonminitour"/><ref name="e!onlinelateralus"/> and art metal.<ref name="33 things"/><ref name="mtvnewssystema"/><ref name="munge">{{cite web | authorMilano, Brett| year=2006| title=Power Tool: Maynard James Keenan and band craft epic art-metal | format=HTML | work=Boston Herald | url=http://theedge.bostonherald.com/musicNews/view.bg?articleid=139842 | accessdate=2006-05-27}}</ref> Simultaneously, the band expressed their kinship with one of their prime influences, King Crimson, whose first albums are considered to have pioneered [[progressive rock]], by launching a joint mini-tour. Comparisons between the two bands were made, calling the bands "the once and future kings of progressive rock".<ref name="kingcrimsonminitour"/> Reviews of ''Lateralus'' often considered it to be progressive rock,<ref name="rollingstonelateralus"/><ref name="AMG_Lateralus_review"/> while others favored its heavier counterpart, [[progressive metal]].<ref name="AllMusic Biography"/><ref name="soberencephale"/> However, longtime King Crimson member [[Robert Fripp]] downplayed any influence his band had on Tool. In an interview with Tool, he touched briefly on how the two bands relate to each other:

<blockquote>"Do you hear the influence? There's just one figure where I hear an influence, just one. It was a piece we were developing that we dropped. And it's almost exactly the same figure: three note arpeggio with a particular accent from the guitar. So I do not think you could have heard it. That's the only thing." (Robert Fripp during a "Tool Army" exclusive interview)<ref>{{cite web | title= Tool Army exclusive interview | url=http://www.toolarmy.com/home/ | accessdate=2006-09-17}}</ref></blockquote>
Unsurprisingly, the band itself has a [[Satire|satirical]] point of view on this debate:

<blockquote>"As far as the prog references go, we embrace them. However, we would prefer our new moniker, which is a Mulligan stew of progressive rock, Bulgarian folk metal, rock <U+2019>n<U+2019> roll, <U+2019>80s disco and Christian rap that we like to call Munge." (Maynard James Keenan cited in Boston Herald, 2006)<ref name="munge"/></blockquote>

===Influence on other bands===
Meanwhile, Tool has impacted newer bands, such as the [[nu metal]] genre as a whole.<ref>{{cite web | author= Sean Richardson | title =Perfect circles - Tool connect on Lateralus | work =The Boston Phoenix | date =May 10, 2001 | url =http://72.166.46.24/boston/music/top/documents/01532143.htm | accessdate =2007-05-25 | quote=[...] today Tool are the well-respected pre-Korn godfathers of rock radio. In a dubious attempt to legitimize this claim, the rock press has accorded a soapbox to one of its fiercest enemies, Fred Durst. <U+201C>Tool<U+2019>s probably the best band on the planet. They<U+2019>re too good. They know something that the rest of the world doesn<U+2019>t know,<U+201D> goes the oft-repeated [...] quote from an MTV News interview with the Limp Bizkit frontman. Given the source, that<U+2019>s a decidedly half-ass compliment; listen to the detuned, Undertow-style rantings of Deftones, System of a Down, or Korn themselves to get a better grasp of Tool<U+2019>s towering influence on new metal.}}</ref> For example, Keenan's unique style of singing has been repeatedly seen influencing artists such as [[Pete Loeffler]] of [[Chevelle]].<ref>{{cite web | last =Assar | first =Vijith | title =Lucky 'Thirteen': Keenan bolsters potence | work =The Cavalier Daily | date =September 30, 2003 | url =http://www.cavalierdaily.com/CVArticle.asp?ID=16988&pid=1052 | accessdate =2007-05-09 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last =Rich | first =Robert | title =Chevelle to play in Austin, remains unique despite criticism | work =The Daily Texan | date =May 9, 2007 | url =http://media.www.dailytexanonline.com/media/storage/paper410/news/2007/05/09/LifeArts/Chevelle.To.Play.In.Austin.Remains.Unique.Despite.Criticism-2897640.shtml | accessdate =2007-05-09 }}</ref> When asked about "these bands who list [[Tool]] as an influence" during an interview with the Australian music magazine Drum Media Keenan replied:

<blockquote>"I do not really see the connection. Because there is some intensity in some of our songs, I think these bands pick up the surface noise, and that's their influence. [...] When I hear these loud, goofy posturing idiots jumping up and down, more concerned about their hairdos than their music, it's just we do not do that, what am I missing? There's nothing to the music that moves me, or compels me to want to sit down and listen to it, which is unfortunate. Maybe I'm just a cynical old bastard."<ref>{{cite web | year = 2001 | month = July | title= Happy Meals Versus Tool Albums | url=http://toolshed.down.net/articles/index.php?action=view-article&id=July_2001--Drum_Media.html | accessdate=2006-09-17}}</ref></blockquote>

==Visual arts==
An integral part of Tool's work as a band is to incorporate influences of other works of art in their music videos, live shows,<ref>{{cite web | last =Peerman | first =Lucas | title =Tool's gold: Progressive rock band jewel of the underground scene | work =Las Cruces Sun-News | date =May 3, 2007 | url =http://www.lcsun-news.com/pulse/ci_5804146 | accessdate =2007-05-09 }}</ref> and album packaging.<ref name="newsgrammypackage">{{cite web | publisher = [[Blabbermouth.net]] | title = Tool Guitarist Wins Grammy For 'Best Recording Package' | url=http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=66850 | date = [[2007-02-11]] | accessdate = 2007-04-09 | quote = We always try to think of something that's never been done before, you know, as far as album packaging, and I've been a fan of stereoscopic photography my whole life and belong to the Southern California Stereoscopic Club [...] And we thought if we could get this to work with our budget, you know, and put this out, it would be really unique and reflecting, you know, a lot of the artwork that I appreciate from the '70s. }}</ref> In particular, [[Adam Jones]] doubles as the band's art director and director of their music videos.<ref name="alexgreyinterview">{{cite web | author = Jonathan Drew | title = MUSIC MEETS ART Name the band Tool's fave artist | work = The Associated Press | url=http://asap.ap.org/stories/575717.s | date =11 May, 2006 | accessdate = 2007-05-26 }}</ref> Another expression of this kinship between the band's music and visual arts is an entire website "dedicated to the arts and influences" on the band, [http://www.dissectional.com dissectional.com].

===Music videos===
:''See also: [[Tool discography#Music videos|Tool discography]]''
[[Image:Tool-Sober-video-screencap.jpg|thumb|right|Screencap from "[[Sober (song)|Sober]]", directed by [[Adam Jones]] and Fred Stuhr.]]
With the exception of "[[Hush (Tool song)|Hush]]", all of Tool's music videos feature [[stop-motion animation]] created by Jones, in a style similar to the [[Brothers Quay]]. Many were created with the help of outside artists such as [[Chet Zar]],<ref name="LiveDesign">{{cite web | last =Sandberg | first =Marian | title =Tool Time | work =Live Design | date =Nov 1, 2006 | url =http://livedesignonline.com/concerts/tool_time/index.html | accessdate =2007-05-09 }}</ref> [[Alex Grey]],<ref name="LiveDesign"/> and [[Osseus Labyrint]].<ref name="Rockdetector">{{cite web | author = Garry Sharpe-Young | title = Rockdetector Biography | work = rockdetector.com | url=http://www.rockdetector.com/officialbio,9409.sm | date =April 16, 2007 | accessdate = 2007-05-25 }}</ref>

Out of seven music videos, the band members make appearances in only the first two, because otherwise "people start latching onto the personalities involved rather than listening to the music."<ref name="much"/> Their "Sober" music video, where "evil little men dwell in a dark dungeon with meat coursing through pipes in the wall,"<ref name="soberencephale">{{cite web | author = Greg Heller | title = Weird Album Title for Tool | url=http://www.rollingstone.com/artists/tool/articles/story/5931985/weird_album_title_for_tool | year = 2001 | month = January | accessdate = 2007-04-09 }}</ref> has gained accolades, with the ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' calling it a groundbreaking, epic clip,<ref name="soberencephale"/> and ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' voting it "Best Clip".<ref name="Rockdetector"/>

No videos have been released to accompany any of their songs off their latest release, ''10,000 Days''. The video for "[[Vicarious (song)|Vicarious]]" was "nearly finished" in July 2006<ref>{{cite web | author = Blair MacKenzie Blake | title = Tool Newsletter | url=http://www.toolband.com/news/letter/2006_07.php | year = 2006 | month = July | accessdate = 2006-08-03 }}</ref> but has yet to be released.

===Album artwork===
Tool has a reputation for "odd"<ref name="FresnoBee" /> and "some of the most innovative album packaging in the industry."<ref name="alexgreyinterview"/> While Adam Jones is responsible for most of the band's artwork in general, ''[[<U+00C6>nima]]''<ref>{{cite web
| url=http://toolshed.down.net/faq/faq.html
| title=G4
| work=The Tool FAQ
| author=Kabir Akhtar
| format=TXT
| quote=The CD cover (<U+00C6>nima) has the Smokebox amidst a moving field of green eyes. That image was created by Adam and Cam de Leon.
}}</ref> and ''[[Salival]]''<ref>{{cite web
| url=http://www.happypencil.com/store.phtml?itemId=22&gid=3
| title=Salival Figure
| work=Happypencil Store
| quote=An ethereal figure desires to equally give and receive, straining to embrace everything, including itself. Original painting for Tool's Salival DVD release, prior to 3-D image mapping for use on the package cover.
}}</ref> included artwork by [[Cam de Leon]], ''[[Lateralus]]''<ref>{{cite web
| url=http://www.popmatters.com/columns/stephens/020508.shtml
| title= High Art: Alex Grey and the Chapel of Sacred Mirrors
| work=PopMatters
| accessdate=2007-06-12
| date=May 8, 2002
| author=Michael Stephens}}</ref> and ''[[10,000 Days]]''<ref name="alexgreyinterview"/> featured work created by [[Alex Grey]]. ''<U+00C6>nima'' was nominated for<ref>{{cite web
| url=http://toolshed.down.net/faq/faq.html | title=D11
| work=The Tool FAQ | accessdate=2007-05-12
| author=Kabir Akhtar }}</ref> and ''10,000 Days'' was awarded with the [[Grammy Award for Best Recording Package]].<ref name="49thgrammyawards"/> As art director of ''10,000 Days'', Adam Jones worked to create packaging that features a pair of [[stereoscopic]] lenses for viewing 3-D artwork and photos. Jones has been a lifelong fan of stereoscopic photography, and expressed a desire for the packaging to be unique within budget, as well as reflecting 70s artwork that he appreciates.<ref name="newsgrammypackage"/> The band logo on ''10,000 Days'' resembles the word "fool".<ref>{{cite web
| url = http://www.sputnikmusic.com/news.php?newsid=303
| title = Tool reveal new album artwork
| author = Alien Six
| publisher = [[Sputnikmusic]]
| date = [[2006-03-21]]
| accessdate = 2007-06-15
}}</ref>

===Live shows===
{{seealso|Tool tours}}
[[Image:Tool live mannheim 2006.jpg|280px|thumb|Tool performing live in 2006, showcasing an elaborate light show, using ''10,000 Days'' artwork as backdrop.]]

Following the first tours in the early nineties, Tool has performed as a headline act in world tours and major festivals such as [[Coachella]] (2006) and [[Big Day Out]] (2007). They have been joined on stage by numerous musicians, including [[Serj Tankian]], [[John Dolmayan]], [[Zack de la Rocha]], [[Scott Reeder]], [[Robert Fripp]], [[Mike Patton]], [[Kirk Hammett]], among other artists, such as experimental arts duo [[Osseus Labyrint]].<ref name="Osseus live">{{cite web | year=2002 | url=http://www.blistering.com/fastpage/fpengine.php/link/1/templateid/4970/tempidx/5009/menuid/5 | work=Blistering.com| title=Tool, The Melvins, Osseus Labyrint - [[April 24]], 2002 - Sydney, Australia @ Sydney Entertainment Centre | accessdate=2007-05-25 | author=Kev Truong }}</ref> They have covered songs by [[Ted Nugent]],<ref name="NugentKyuss">{{cite web | last =Augusto | first =Troy J. | title =Tool | work =Variety | date =April 2, 1998 | url =http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117467336.html?categoryid=34&cs=1 | accessdate =2007-05-10 }}</ref> [[Kyuss]],<ref name="NugentKyuss"/> [[Led Zeppelin]], and the [[Ramones]].<ref>{{cite web | last =Rothman | first =Robin A. | title =Tool Take Radio City-''Rockers salute the Ramones during epic set'' | work =Rolling Stone | date =August 14, 2002 | url =http://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/5934876/tool_take_radio_city | accessdate =2007-05-10 }}</ref>

Live shows on Tool's headline tours differ from many other rock concerts.<ref name="flathatreview">{{cite web | year=2001 | url=http://flathat.wm.edu/October052001/reviewsstory5.shtml | work=The Flat Hat:Reviews| title=Tool thrills audience | accessdate=2007-04-07 | author=Keith P. McManus }}</ref> The band members are placed quite unusually, with singer Maynard James Keenan lining up in the second row with drummer Danny Carey on an elevated platform, while guitarist Adam Jones and bassist Justin Chancellor stand in first row at the respective edges of the stage.<ref name="nytimesmadisonsquare">{{cite web | date=October 6, 2001 | url = http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9C01EFDB143CF935A35753C1A9679C8B63 | work=The New York Times| title=Flailing Wildly to Escape the Darkness | accessdate=2007-06-09 | author=Jon Pareles }}</ref> No followspots or live cameras are used,<ref name="plsnews">{{cite web |date=October 16, 2006 | url=http://www.plsn.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=1316&Itemid=101 | work=Projection, Light and Staging News| title=700 Clips for 10,000 Days | accessdate=2007-04-07 | author=Rob Ludwig }}</ref> instead the band employs a great amount of backlighting, to direct the focus away from the bandmembers, to big screens in the back and the crowd.<ref name="flathatreview"/> In particular, the resulting "dark spaces are [...] for Maynard. A lot of the songs are a personal journey for him [...] and he feels more comfortable in the shadows."<ref name="plsnews"/>
The big screens are used to playback "looped clips that aren<U+2019>t tracked to a song like a music video. The band has never used any sort of timecode. They<U+2019>ve always made sure the video can change on-the-fly, in a way that can be improvised. [...] The show is never the same twice."<ref name="plsnews"/> During the ''10,000 Days'' tour, the video material consisted of over 6 hours of material, created by Adam Jones, his wife Camella Grace, [[Chet Zar]], Meats Meyer and Rob Ludwig (lighting and video designer during the tour).<ref name="plsnews"/> Some of the material created by Chet Zar has been released on his DVD ''Disturb the Normal''.<ref name="chetzardisturb">{{cite web | year=2006 | url=http://www.chetzar.com/dvdfiles/whatisit.html | work=Disturb the Normal description| title=What is it? | accessdate=2007-04-07 | author=Chet Zar }}</ref>

==Etymology==
[[Image:Tool-logo-early.jpg|thumb|right|The "Wrench", one of Tool's early logos, created by longtime collaborator [[Cam de Leon]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.lowelaw.com/articles/ | title=Visual Artist Cam De Leon's Lawsuit Against Rock Band TOOL Allowed to Proceed | work=Press release | accessdate=2007-06-15 | year=2006 | author=Lowe Law Lawyers agency}}</ref>]]
The band has circulated several stories surrounding the origin of their name. One of the most vital speculations revolved around [[lachrymology]], a [[pseudophilosophy]] that the band has stated was founded in 1949 by Ronald P. Vincent after the death of his wife in a snow plowing accident. Drummer [[Danny Carey]] alleged that the name "Tool" means that the band served its fans as a tool through which those people would come to understand the concept of lachrymology.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.toolarmy.com/toolband/lachrymology/lachrymology.php?key=fob | title=Let Not My Tears Fall Unnoticed: Being the Secret Joys of a Lachrymist | work=toolarmy.com | accessdate=2007-05-06 | author=Blair MacKenzie Blake}}</ref> However, it is more likely that the band made this up in order to create a unique backdrop, since singer Maynard James Keenan gave a more direct approach to explaining his band's name in an interview in 1994:

<blockquote>"Tool is exactly what it sounds like: It's a big dick. It's a wrench. It's also what it sounds like: It's a verb, it's a digging factor. It's an active process of searching, as in use us, we are a shovel, we are the match, we're the blotter of acid, your tool; use us as a catalyst in your process of finding out whatever it is you need to find out, or whatever it is you're trying to achieve."<ref>{{cite web | url=http://toolshed.down.net/articles/index.php?action=view-article&id=April_1994--RayGun.html | title=Tool Rules | work=RayGun Magazine | accessdate=2006-08-27 | year=1994 | author=Moon Unit Zappa}}</ref></blockquote>

